            },
            "answer_text": "He was fluent in many languages, and he had the working equivalent of a bachelors or masters degree in many areas, able to converse as an expert. In several areas\u2014philosophy, mathematics, and logic\u2014he had the equivalent of a PhD. He could quote all the great literature of the world, from the Greeks to Shakespeare and beyond, at the drop of a hat, always finding something appropriate for the occasion. But beyond all those achievements (which are really in the realm of knowledge) he had much more: an almost unique talent for taking any aspect of this knowledge and whittling it down to its simplest possible explanation \u2014 understanding that while there is always more to know, things are rarely as difficult or obscure as the experts insist on making them. After all, there is no Nobel Prize for either mathematics or philosophy. Instead, Lord Russell achieved his Nobel Prize in the area of Literature\u2026 specifically, his essays that made his knowledge accessible to others and taught the human race all it needed to know about survival and compassion. ",
