                "name": "Irwin Klien",
                "href": "/profile/Irwin-Klien"
            },
            "answer_text": "In many ways he was extremely intelligent. His mathematical skills were extraordinary. His Book Principia Mathmatica with Alfred North Whitehead is a classic. He also had a gift for writing. He was fluent, very clear and humorous. Unfortunately many of his ideas were weak, and some were just silly. He was a pacifist through both WWI and WWII, yet he later took the position that the USA should direct a preemptive nuclear strike against the Soviet Union. He maintained this position for 3 years and then changed his mind. He then claimed he never said any such thing. When faced with innumerable newspaper, newsreels, and TV interviews he claimed he was just kidding. No one who viewed these materials believed it. He also went from position to position in Philosophy. Many of them flatly contradicted his previous position. He was, I believe, an inventive, but not a deep thinker. ",
